sec.p:
Late‐stage functionalization of aminoacids and biomolecules by synthetic groups offers attractive prospects in chemical biology and can serve several purposes, including spectroscopic detection, imaging, and subsequent chemical elaboration toward more complex architectures.[

1
, 
2

] Selectivity and efficiency are key issues for the applicability of these strategies,[

3

] but mild conditions are also desirable to ensure stability of the products and avoid competing side reactions. Among groups of interest to be transferred, fluorine‐containing groups, and particularly CF3 have attracted much attention[

4

] due to their ability to modify metabolic and pharmacokinetic profiles of drug candidates,[

5

] their implication in structural proteomics[

6

] or their effect on protein folding.[

7

] Harnessing the potential of radical processes to take place in biological media,[

8

] several methods for the introduction of CF3 groups in aminoacids have been reported.[

4

] These methods mostly rely on radical manifolds using CF3SO2Na in combination with radical initiators such as tert‐butyl‐hydroperoxide (TBHP),[

9

] or CF3SO2Na or CF3I under photoredox catalysis with iridium complexes.[

10
, 
11

] Under these conditions, (hetero)aromatic sites such as His, Trp, Tyr, and Phe residues or nucleophilic Cys are often reactive and this can impair selectivity, although careful tuning of the pH enhances control over the selectivity. Alternative trifluoromethylating sources include hypervalent iodine derivatives and late‐stage modification of peptides and proteins by introduction of an aryl‐CF3 group at cysteine residues with diaryliodonium salts has been reported.[

12

]

The indole‐based aminoacid tryptophane (Trp) is widely present in biomolecules, as at least 90% of native proteins have one Trp residue incorporated in the primary sequence, but only at a frequency of 1.4%, which makes this residue an interesting target for post‐functionalization of peptides.[

13

] A copper‐catalyzed trifluoromethylation of indoles using Togni reagent has been reported[

14

] and visible‐light‐activated methods for the introduction of CF3 groups in Trp residues using iridium‐based photoredox catalysts,[

10

],[

15

] reductive catalysis[

16

], or radical initiators[

9

] have been developed. These approaches have led the way, and synthetic protocols using mild radical generation conditions and/or earth‐abundant metals require further attention while selectivity in peptidic sequences bearing several reactive heteroaromatic residues can be difficult to achieve.[

17

] Figure 1.

Drawing inspiration from metalloenzymes,[
18
] complexes of earth‐abundant metals bearing redox‐active ligands can engage in controlled radical mechanisms by storing and releasing electrons from their ligands.[
19 , 20 , 21 , 22
] This circumvents the variation of metallic oxidation state and enables them to operate under very mild conditions. A copper complex with redox‐active iminosemiquinone ligands Cu(SQ)2,[
23
] (Scheme 1, SQ : iminosemiquinone) has been shown to perform the controlled release of CF3 • radicals and subsequent functionalization of indolic derivatives in organic solvents.[
24
] Aiming to emulate this behavior in biological media, we turned our attention to the design of a water‐soluble version of this complex. Here, we report a radical trifluoromethylation protocol for indolic residues that does not require light activation or radical initiators, and performs the selective functionalization of tryptophane residues. This catalyst operates with a distinctive selectivity as tryptophane residues can be selectively functionalized in the presence of other heteroaromatic residues, such as tyrosine, histidine, and phenylalanine.

The synthesis of a water‐soluble redox‐active copper complex was targeted by introducing a carboxylic acid functional group on the pendant aromatic ring of an aminophenol ligand. Proligand 1 was prepared by refluxing di‐tBu‐catechol and 4‐aminobenzoic acid in the presence of a catalytic amount of Et3N in 56%, yield and its structure was confirmed by X‐ray crystallography (Scheme 1). Subsequent complexation with CuCl, and using PPh4 + as a counterion, led to the isolation of copper complex 2 in 81% yield as confirmed by HRMS (high‐resolution mass spectrometry). Several recrystallization attempts led only to weakly diffracting crystals and could only confirm the connectivity, although no exploitable bond lengths could be obtained. UV‐vis spectroscopy of 2 was performed in methanol (Figure 2a) and features a broad band centered around 786 nm. In analogy with the parent Cu(SQ)2 complex, this band could be indicative of an intervalence charge transfer.[
23
]

The X‐band EPR spectrum of complex 2 was recorded at 100 K in methanol. As previously observed for the parent complex Cu(SQ)2, the two radical spins are strongly antiferromagnetically coupled giving rise to the observed singlet ground state, which is reflected in the EPR spectrum by an almost isolated Cu2+.[

23

] Indeed, the EPR parameters obtained from the simulation show an axial g value with 63,65Cu hyperfine coupling close to values expected from a single ion Cu2+ (Figure 2b).[

23

] These results confirm that 2 is a CuII complex with antiferromagnetically coupled radical ligands.

The electrochemical behavior of 2 was studied in both DMSO and water with a glassy carbon disk as working electrode. In DMSO (Figure 3a), the complex exhibits two reversible monoelectronic reduction waves at E1/2 = ‐0.86 V and ‐1.19 V versus Fc+/Fc, respectively (or ‐0.36 V and ‐0.69 V vs. AgCl/Ag, respectively), and two quasi‐reversible monoelectronic oxidation waves at E1/2 = ‐0.46 V and ‐0.08 V versus Fc+/Fc, respectively (or + 0.04 V and + 0.42 V vs. AgCl/Ag, respectively). As compared to the parent [Cu(SQ)2] complex,[

23

] all waves are shifted to more anodic potentials, as expected from the introduction of the electron‐withdrawing carboxylic acid group on the ligands. The reduction waves are attributed to the sequential reduction of the two ligands from iminosemiquinones to aminophenols, and the oxidation waves to the sequential oxidation of the two ligands from iminosemiquinones into iminobenzoquinones. In water (Figure 2b), the two reduction waves almost merge together, resulting in a main cathodic peak at ‐0.29 V versus AgCl/Ag along with a shoulder at ‐0.15 V and only one anodic peak at + 0.05 V. Similarly, only one irreversible oxidation signal is observed at Epa = +0.86 V versus AgCl/Ag. The oxidation and reduction of the two ligands occur thus almost simultaneously in water and sequentially in DMSO.

Reactivity of complex 2 in radical CF3 group transfer was first assessed in comparison[

24

] with its nonwater‐soluble analogue Cu(SQ)2. Boc‐tryptamine 3, soluble in both CH2Cl2 and MeOH, was selected as a model substrate, and hypervalent iodine‐based electrophilic derivative 4 (Togni reagent: 1‐trifluoromethyl‐1,2‐benziodoxol‐3‐(1H)‐one) was selected as CF3 source. The corresponding monotrifluoromethylated adduct 5 functionalized at the 2‐position of the indole ring was isolated in 49% yield under the following conditions: 1.5 equiv. of 4, 20 mol% of 2 in MeOH at reflux for 7 hours (Scheme 2). Varying the catalyst loading to 10 mol% led to decreased yield, while 30 mol% led to polysubstitution and side products (Table S2). Performing the reaction with parent complex Cu(SQ)2 as a catalyst in CH2Cl2, 5 was obtained in 53% yield, confirming that both complexes have comparable catalytic activities. Switching to a model dipeptide 6 (Ac‐WG‐NH2), reaction conditions were screened (Table 1). In pure methanol (entries 1–3), the dipeptide signal disappears, suggesting that 6 either degrades or precipitates. DMSO and water are commonly used as co‐solvents for peptide functionalization under radical conditions[

25

],[

26

] and performing the reaction in DMSO/H2O 1:1 at 50 °C using 3 equiv. of Togni reagent 4 led to trifluoromethylated adduct 7 in 60% yield (entry 6). The reaction was followed by HPLC at 214 nm and full conversion of 6 into 7 is observed after 7 hours, while a small amount of bis‐trifluoromethylated by‐product was formed. All products were identified by LC‐MS (see Supporting Information Section 7.1). A blank experiment conducted in the absence of a catalyst led only to trace amounts of 7 (entry 7), thus demonstrating the essential role of complex 2 as catalyst.

Having established the efficiency of complex 2 toward the functionalization of tryptophane residues, we aimed to assess its reactivity toward other aromatic aminoacids including tyrosine (Tyr, Y), histidine (His, H), and phenylalanine (Phe, F) (method A, Scheme 4). As a comparison, oxidative conditions using CF3SO2Na as a CF3 source adapted from reported literature procedures[
9 , 27
] were selected (method B, Scheme 4). While both methods enable the C2‐functionalization of Trp into 8b in 64% and 70% yields, respectively, the copper‐catalyzed manifold (method A) exhibits a strong selectivity toward Trp. Low reactivity toward tyrosine residues was observed as compound 11b is obtained in 18% yield and only trace amounts of functionalized histidine 12b and phenylalanine 13b are detected. By contrast, method B performs CF3 transfer on Tyr (45% yield), His (8% yield) and Phe (9% yield), and is therefore less selective. To further evaluate the selectivity, intermolecular competition experiments were carried out on an equimolar mixture of Ac‐GGWG‐NH2 and Ac‐GGYG‐NH2 (Scheme S13). With method A, we observe a selectivity for Trp with Ac‐GGW(CF3)G‐NH2 8b formed in 64% yield and Ac‐GGY(CF3)G‐NH2 11b in 18% yield. Under these conditions, the starting Trp‐containing peptide Ac‐GGWG‐NH2 was fully consumed, and 25% of the isomer products of Ac‐GGW(CF3)2G‐NH2 with CF3 incorporation in aromatic positions were observed (Figure S50). With method B, Ac‐GGW(CF3)G‐NH2 8b is formed in 49% yield and Ac‐GGY(CF3)G‐NH2 11b in 10% yield, while unreacted Ac‐GGWG‐NH2 (26%) and Ac‐GGYG‐NH2 (90%) remain. A second addition of the reagents (6 equiv. Langlois salt CF3SO2Na, 2.5 equiv. TBHP, and 0.1 equiv. FeCl2.4H2O) to the crude reaction mixture led to full conversion into a mixture of bis‐trifluoromethylated Ac‐GGW(CF3)2G‐NH2 position isomers, and 62% Ac‐GGY(CF3)G‐NH2 was formed, while 32% Ac‐GGYG‐NH2 11a remained (Figure S51). These experiments suggest that method A offers milder reaction conditions than method B, thus avoiding poly‐trifluoromethylation of the indole motif in Trp.
